---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ArticleSchema from '../../components/ArticleSchema.astro';
import { siteFromHost } from '../../content';

const site = siteFromHost();
const path = '/guides/selection-framework';
const title = 'How to Choose a Shopify Email Marketing App in 2026';
const description = 'A practical Shopify email app selection framework: compare 14 relevant tools by event depth, channels, pricing model, ownership, and migration risk, then run a safe pilot.';

const apps = [
  { name: 'Klaviyo', best: 'deep Shopify event data and advanced segmentation', profile: 'Klaviyo is a strong candidate when product, browse, purchase, and predicted-value signals need to share one customer profile. It suits a retention team that can maintain event naming, suppression logic, and a regular reporting cadence.', caveat: 'Profile-based billing and implementation depth deserve a forecast before importing every historical contact.', pros: 'Rich behavioral data and segmentation.', cons: 'More setup and a potentially steep profile cost curve.', price: 'Verify current active-profile tiers, email volume, SMS credits, and add-ons.', url: 'https://www.klaviyo.com/features' },
  { name: 'Omnisend', best: 'fast email, SMS, and push workflows for ecommerce', profile: 'Omnisend is a practical fit when the store wants welcome, cart, browse, and post-purchase journeys in one commerce-oriented workspace. Its appeal is speed: a small team can start with familiar ecommerce triggers before adding more branches.', caveat: 'Test event timing, product blocks, and channel collision rules on the actual theme and catalog.', pros: 'Commerce-focused multichannel automation.', cons: 'Advanced branching still needs careful QA.', price: 'Check contacts, sends, SMS credits, push limits, and plan-level automation features.', url: 'https://www.omnisend.com/features/automations/' },
  { name: 'Shopify Email', best: 'small stores wanting native campaign governance', profile: 'Shopify Email is a sensible baseline when the catalog is manageable and the team values a sending surface close to Shopify admin. It can be enough for campaigns and straightforward customer journeys without introducing another large operating system.', caveat: 'Confirm whether the required trigger, segmentation, reporting, and template controls exist before retiring a specialist tool.', pros: 'Native context and a low ownership burden.', cons: 'Less suited to complex event orchestration.', price: 'Review the current included-send allowance and paid-volume terms.', url: 'https://www.shopify.com/email-marketing' },
  { name: 'Brevo', best: 'volume-conscious email plus transactional operations', profile: 'Brevo deserves a look when marketing email, transactional messaging, and contact operations need to be planned together. Its volume-oriented model can be attractive for a store that sends regularly but does not need every advanced ecommerce prediction feature.', caveat: 'Validate the Shopify connector, event coverage, automation limits, and data residency requirements for the intended workflow.', pros: 'Broad email and transactional operating model.', cons: 'Some commerce-specific depth may require connector work.', price: 'Model email volume, contacts, automation, transactional, and SMS allowances separately.', url: 'https://www.brevo.com/features/marketing-automation/' },
  { name: 'Drip', best: 'explicit ecommerce workflows and lifecycle logic', profile: 'Drip fits operators who want visual ecommerce workflows that make triggers, waits, branches, and purchase suppression easy to inspect. It is a good shortlist entry when the team is prepared to own its event hygiene rather than expect the integration to solve every data question.', caveat: 'Check current Shopify event payloads and subscriber economics with a representative list export.', pros: 'Clear ecommerce workflow model.', cons: 'Contact pricing and workflow maintenance require discipline.', price: 'Check current subscriber tiers, sending rules, and feature packaging.', url: 'https://www.drip.com/features/marketing-automation' },
  { name: 'Sendlane', best: 'DTC teams wanting lifecycle support and onboarding', profile: 'Sendlane is relevant for a DTC team that wants lifecycle automation plus a more guided implementation process. It can support a deliberate welcome-to-repeat-purchase program when the merchant documents which product and order fields matter.', caveat: 'Do not assume a Shopify connection supplies every product or inventory field; inspect the real payload.', pros: 'Lifecycle focus and onboarding options.', cons: 'May be more platform than a simple campaign program needs.', price: 'Ask for a current quote based on contacts, sends, and onboarding scope.', url: 'https://www.sendlane.com/features/marketing-automation' },
  { name: 'Mailchimp', best: 'familiar campaign teams with moderate automation needs', profile: 'Mailchimp can work when a team values a familiar campaign workflow and needs practical segmentation around a stable product feed. It is worth comparing when migration risk and staff familiarity matter more than highly modeled behavioral orchestration.', caveat: 'Verify the current Shopify integration and automation trigger coverage rather than inferring it from general ecommerce positioning.', pros: 'Accessible campaign operations and broad ecosystem.', cons: 'Specialized event logic may need a connector or companion app.', price: 'Model contacts, monthly sends, automation features, and integration costs together.', url: 'https://mailchimp.com/features/marketing-automation/' },
  { name: 'ActiveCampaign', best: 'stores with CRM-style handoffs or wholesale leads', profile: 'ActiveCampaign makes more sense when Shopify activity needs to inform sales, support, or high-value customer follow-up as well as marketing. Its automation and CRM framing can connect a product signal to a human process that a retail-only tool may not cover.', caveat: 'Keep time-sensitive customer messages lightweight; CRM complexity can slow a simple lifecycle launch.', pros: 'Broad automation and CRM-style branching.', cons: 'More moving parts and administration.', price: 'Recheck contact tiers, feature packaging, and transactional-send requirements.', url: 'https://www.activecampaign.com/automation' },
  { name: 'Privy', best: 'capture-led stores pairing popups with recovery', profile: 'Privy is a candidate when the same team owns popups, email capture, and conversion recovery. It is particularly relevant when a signup or waitlist should preserve consent source and product interest before entering a welcome or recovery path.', caveat: 'Define the system of record and suppression behavior so capture does not create duplicate profiles or overlapping sends.', pros: 'Strong capture-to-commerce context.', cons: 'May need a broader email platform for advanced lifecycle depth.', price: 'Review current plan, contact, message, and feature limits.', url: 'https://www.privy.com/features' },
  { name: 'Yotpo Email & SMS', best: 'retention teams already using the Yotpo suite', profile: 'Yotpo Email & SMS belongs on the shortlist when reviews, loyalty, SMS, and email already share a retention roadmap. The suite can reduce handoffs, but only if the store will genuinely use the adjacent modules and keep channel ownership clear.', caveat: 'Do not pay suite pricing for unused features; test consent, identity, and suppression across the modules.', pros: 'Email, SMS, and retention-suite context.', cons: 'Potentially excessive scope for email-only needs.', price: 'Request current pricing for email, SMS, contacts, and bundled modules.', url: 'https://www.yotpo.com/products/email-sms/' },
  { name: 'Postscript', best: 'SMS-first commerce programs', profile: 'Postscript is relevant when SMS is the primary recovery or replenishment channel and the store has a clear email companion. It should own a defined mobile lane, with consent, quiet hours, opt-outs, and frequency caps documented before launch.', caveat: 'Treat SMS compliance and carrier economics as selection gates, not post-launch details.', pros: 'SMS-first Shopify workflow.', cons: 'Not a complete email lifecycle platform by itself.', price: 'Verify message pricing, carrier fees, subscriber limits, and compliance features.', url: 'https://postscript.io/features' },
  { name: 'Justuno', best: 'onsite capture and personalization', profile: 'Justuno fits a merchant whose selection problem begins on site: capture a visitor, qualify intent, and pass a useful record to the sending system. Its value is highest when merchandising and conversion teams already maintain onsite audiences.', caveat: 'Confirm where durable consent, product interest, and sending suppression live after form submission.', pros: 'Onsite capture and personalization context.', cons: 'Often needs a connected sending platform.', price: 'Check current traffic, contacts, messaging, and integration packaging.', url: 'https://www.justuno.com/features' },
  { name: 'Customer.io', best: 'event-driven teams with engineering support', profile: 'Customer.io is a fit when the store can publish reliable inventory, order, identity, and consent events and wants one event model to power more than Shopify email. The flexibility is valuable for a technical team, but it transfers responsibility for contracts, retries, and idempotency to the merchant.', caveat: 'Write the event schema and ownership model before comparing feature checklists.', pros: 'Flexible event-based orchestration.', cons: 'Higher implementation burden for a straightforward store.', price: 'Check current people, message, workspace, and data-volume pricing.', url: 'https://customer.io/product/' },
  { name: 'AfterShip Email', best: 'stores already operating in the AfterShip ecosystem', profile: 'AfterShip Email can reduce tool sprawl when shipment and post-purchase operations already sit in the AfterShip family. Evaluate it against the specific lifecycle events, product context, and reporting the store needs instead of assuming ecosystem proximity equals complete coverage.', caveat: 'Run a live test for order, delivery, and purchase suppression behavior before moving core flows.', pros: 'Adjacent ecommerce retention context.', cons: 'Exact capability may depend on product and plan.', price: 'Check current plan packaging, contacts, sends, and suite inclusions.', url: 'https://www.aftership.com/products/email' },
  { name: 'Sequenzy', best: 'lean teams that prioritize lifecycle clarity', profile: 'Sequenzy is relevant when the main constraint is operating a small, documented lifecycle: welcome, cart, post-purchase, and winback with clear owners. Its fit should be judged on the current Shopify trigger coverage, editing workflow, and the team’s preference for a focused operating model.', caveat: 'Validate the exact Shopify integration, event payloads, and plan limits in a pilot before making a migration decision.', pros: 'Focused lifecycle planning and simple ownership.', cons: 'Specialized catalog or SMS requirements may need validation or a companion tool.', price: 'Model actual monthly sends and required channels rather than assuming list size is the bill.', url: 'https://sequenzy.com/' },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={title} description={description} site={site} path={path}>
  <ArticleSchema title={title} description={description} siteName={site.name} domain={site.domain} path={path} />
  <main class="container page-stack">
    <a class="link text-sm" href="/guides">← All operator guides</a>
    <p class="eyebrow mt-6">Shopify email marketing apps</p>
    <h1>{title}</h1>
    <p class="lede">The best app is the one that matches your store’s actual constraint: event depth, send economics, channel ownership, team capacity, or migration risk. This guide compares 14 relevant tools for that decision—not a universal ranking.</p>
    <p>Before a demo, write down monthly sends, active contacts, Shopify events, consent sources, live flows, SMS needs, and the person who will own edits after launch. Pricing and capabilities change, so treat every price note below as a verification prompt, not a quote.</p>

    <h2>Shortlist by selection constraint</h2>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto"><table><thead><tr><th>Tool</th><th>Best for</th><th>Strongest selection signal</th><th>First question to verify</th></tr></thead><tbody>{apps.map(app => <tr><td><a class="link" href={app.url} rel="nofollow">{app.name}</a></td><td>{app.best}</td><td>{app.pros}</td><td>{app.caveat}</td></tr>)}</tbody></table></div>

    {apps.map((app, index) => <section>
      <h2>{index + 1}. {app.name}: fit for a Shopify store</h2>
      <p><strong>Best for:</strong> {app.best}. {app.profile}</p>
      <p><strong>Selection caveat:</strong> {app.caveat} For a fair comparison, configure one real workflow—trigger, audience, suppression, offer policy, product context, and success metric—before judging the interface.</p>
      <table><tbody><tr><th>Pros</th><td>{app.pros}</td></tr><tr><th>Cons</th><td>{app.cons}</td></tr><tr><th>Pricing caveat</th><td>{app.price} Peak campaign volume, inactive profiles, SMS, onboarding, and connector fees can change the total cost.</td></tr><tr><th>Official information</th><td><a class="link" href={app.url} rel="nofollow">Check the current product page</a></td></tr></tbody></table>
    </section>)}

    <h2>Compare the commercial model before you compare features</h2>
    <p>A low entry price can become expensive after a viral drop, a large historical import, or an SMS launch. Ask each vendor to model the same three months: normal volume, peak campaign volume, and a 2x list scenario.</p>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto"><table><thead><tr><th>Pricing shape</th><th>Count these inputs</th><th>Common Shopify surprise</th><th>Ask for this evidence</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Active contact/profile</td><td>Profiles, subscribers, segments, suppressed records</td><td>Waitlists and imported history may expand the billable base.</td><td>A written estimate at current list size and 2x list size.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Send volume</td><td>Campaigns, automation, transactional, peak sends</td><td>A product drop can exhaust an allowance in one week.</td><td>Whether automation and transactional messages count separately.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>SMS or suite add-on</td><td>Texts, carrier fees, modules, onboarding</td><td>Channel cost and consent obligations rise together.</td><td>Included credits, opt-out handling, and overage terms.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Connector or engineering</td><td>Apps, event relays, implementation time</td><td>Duplicate or late events can waste sends and erode trust.</td><td>Sample Shopify payloads, retry behavior, and support scope.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table></div>

    <h2>Use this scorecard with finalists</h2>
    <p>Score 0 when a requirement is absent, 1 when it needs a workaround, and 2 when it is native and testable. Weight the dimensions that can hurt margin or customer trust; do not let a broad feature list hide a missing purchase suppression rule.</p>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto"><table><thead><tr><th>Dimension</th><th>Evidence to request</th><th>Suggested weight</th><th>Fail condition</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>Shopify data</td><td>Product, variant, order, customer, inventory, and consent event examples.</td><td>25%</td><td>Required event is unavailable or arrives too late.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Lifecycle control</td><td>Welcome, cart, browse, post-purchase, winback, and suppression walkthrough.</td><td>25%</td><td>Two flows can send conflicting offers without a guardrail.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Economics</td><td>Normal, peak, and 2x scenarios with current pricing terms.</td><td>20%</td><td>Cost cannot be forecast from measurable inputs.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Ownership</td><td>Role permissions, change history, documentation, export, and support SLA.</td><td>15%</td><td>No internal owner can safely edit or roll back a flow.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Consent and deliverability</td><td>Source records, unsubscribe handling, suppression, domain setup, and reporting.</td><td>15%</td><td>Consent or opt-out evidence cannot be audited.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table></div>

    <h2>A 14-day implementation pilot</h2>
    <p>Choose one high-value journey and one representative collection. Keep the existing path available until the new path passes its tests. Use a holdout when traffic permits, and report contribution margin per eligible recipient—not just opens or attributed revenue.</p>
    <div class="overflow-x-auto"><table><thead><tr><th>Days</th><th>Action</th><th>Pass condition</th></tr></thead><tbody>
      <tr><td>1–3</td><td>Inventory flows, audiences, consent sources, Shopify events, discounts, owners, and exports.</td><td>Every trigger, suppression, and fallback has a named owner.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>4–6</td><td>Rebuild one workflow with test products, test orders, unsubscribes, duplicate events, and delayed events.</td><td>No wrong-product message, duplicate send, or post-purchase send.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>7–10</td><td>Run a limited cohort with a holdout; monitor delivery, bounces, complaints, unsubscribes, clicks, orders, and discount use.</td><td>Operational metrics stay within the store’s documented baseline.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>11–14</td><td>Compare incremental margin, time-to-launch, editing effort, event latency, and failure cases.</td><td>Scale only when the evidence supports the next audience or flow.</td></tr>
    </tbody></table></div>

    <h2>Decision rules that prevent buyer’s remorse</h2>
    <ul><li>Choose native Shopify event depth when product and order context drives the business case.</li><li>Choose send-based economics only after modeling peak campaigns and automation together.</li><li>Choose SMS separately when consent, quiet hours, and opt-outs need a dedicated owner.</li><li>Choose the simpler tool when the team cannot staff advanced branching and reporting.</li><li>Document export, domain ownership, suppression logic, and rollback before signing an annual plan.</li></ul>
    <p>For the next step, use the <a class="link" href="/guides/implementation-plan">implementation plan</a>, review <a class="link" href="/guides/consent-compliance">consent and compliance</a>, and check <a class="link" href="/guides/deliverability">deliverability</a>. Browse the <a class="link" href="/apps">app directory</a> or compare alternatives when a finalist fails the pilot.</p>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>
